PUSHWOOSH ANDROID SDK — PRIVACY STATEMENT

This statement describes what the Pushwoosh Android SDK does with data when a
developer (the "Client") integrates it into an application. It is intended to
help the Client complete the Google Play Data Safety form, run vendor and
security reviews, and reference Pushwoosh in the Client's own privacy policy.
It covers the SDK only — not any Client application.


1. ROLES

  - Client (App Developer) — Data Controller. Decides whether to integrate
    the SDK and what data to send through it.
  - Pushwoosh (SDK provider) — Data Processor. Processes data only on the
    Client's instructions, to deliver the service. Pushwoosh does not own the
    data and does not use it for its own purposes.


2. DATA THE SDK COLLECTS AUTOMATICALLY

On initialization the SDK collects a minimal set of technical data needed to
deliver notifications:

  - Push token — issued by Firebase Cloud Messaging (FCM) to address
    notifications to the device.
  - Installation identifier — a randomly generated UUID created by the SDK. It
    is not a hardware identifier (not ANDROID_ID, IMEI, serial number or MAC)
    and not an advertising identifier (not GAID); it does not identify a
    person.
  - Device model and Android version — for correct rendering and
    troubleshooting.
  - Language/locale and time zone — for localization and time-zoned delivery.
  - Application version and SDK version — for compatibility and
    troubleshooting.
  - Approximate location (city/country) — derived from the IP address of the
    last connection for coarse geo-targeting.
  - Aggregated delivery and lifecycle analytics (e.g. delivery success,
    app-open) — for service stability and troubleshooting.

Device model, Android version and language are collected under flags that are
on by default and can be disabled by the Client. Precise location is processed
only as an optional feature, and only if the Client enables geo-targeting and
the end user grants the Android location permission.


3. DATA THE SDK DOES NOT COLLECT

The SDK does not collect cookies, ANDROID_ID, IMEI, MAC address, device serial
number, or the advertising identifier (GAID). On its own initiative it does
not collect names, email addresses, phone numbers, financial data, or
health/medical data.


4. CLIENT-PROVIDED DATA (TAGS, EVENTS, PAYLOAD)

The SDK lets the Client optionally send additional custom data (tags, events,
segments) through its public methods. Pushwoosh receives and processes this
data as-is, solely for the Client's notification targeting. The SDK does not
validate, intentionally collect, or store personal, health or other sensitive
data on its own initiative — whether any such data is sent is entirely the
Client's decision and responsibility.


5. PURPOSE OF PROCESSING

  - App functionality — technical delivery of push notifications to the
    device.
  - Analytics and troubleshooting — aggregated statistics (such as delivery
    success and SDK version) for stability and bug-fixing.


6. DATA RETENTION

Pushwoosh processes data only for as long as necessary to provide the service,
unless a longer retention period is required or permitted by law. Device data
is retained while the device remains active, and inactive devices are purged
automatically. Data is deleted when it is no longer needed to deliver the
service, or earlier on request.


7. SECURITY

All default and built-in SDK endpoints use HTTPS / TLS. The SDK sets no
cleartext-traffic exception (no android:usesCleartextTraffic="true").


8. THIRD-PARTY SHARING

Data is not sold and is not shared with third parties for their own purposes.
The SDK does not use advertising identifiers and does not perform cross-app
tracking. The push token is passed to Firebase Cloud
Messaging (FCM) solely to deliver notifications.


9. OPT-OUT / CONSENT

By default the SDK begins collection and transmission on initialization. To
prevent any transmission before the user has given consent, the Client can
disable SDK communication and enable it only after consent is obtained. The
SDK also supports device/data removal on request, which fully disables further
transmission.


10. CHILDREN

The Pushwoosh SDK is a developer tool and is not directed at children. It does
not knowingly collect personal data of children on its own initiative.
Determining an application's audience and any applicable obligations for
children's data is the Client's responsibility as Data Controller.


11. CONTACT

  - Privacy requests: privacy@pushwoosh.com
  - Report an issue: https://github.com/Pushwoosh
